	<h2 class="story">
		

		

		
		

		

		

		

		<span id="title-174548922" class="story-title"> <a   href="//tech.slashdot.org/story/24/07/20/179242/southwest-airlines-avoids-cloudstrike-issues---thanks-to-windows-31">Southwest Airlines Avoids Cloudstrike Issues - Thanks to Windows 3.1?</a> <span class=" no extlnk"><a class="story-sourcelnk" href="https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/southwest-cloudstrike-windows-3-1/"  title="External link - https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/southwest-cloudstrike-windows-3-1/" target="_blank"> (digitaltrends.com) </a></span></span>

		
		
		<!--<span class="comments commentcnt-174548922" >104</span>-->
		

		
		<!-- comment bubble -->
		
			<span class="comment-bubble"><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/story/24/07/20/179242/southwest-airlines-avoids-cloudstrike-issues---thanks-to-windows-31#comments" title="">104</a></span>
		
	</h2>
	<div class="details" id="details-174548922">
		<span class="story-details">
		<span class="story-views">
			<span class="sodify" onclick="firehose_set_options('color', 'red')" title="Filter Firehose to entries rated red or better"></span><span class="icon-beaker pop1 " alt="Popularity" title="Filter Firehose to entries rated red or better" onclick="firehose_set_options('color', 'red')"><span></span></span> 
		</span>
		</span>
		<span class="story-byline">
	
				
			Posted
				by 
		
		
			
				  EditorDavid
			
		
		

		
		
		<time id="fhtime-174548922" datetime="on Saturday July 20, 2024 @01:34PM">on Saturday July 20, 2024 @01:34PM</time>
		
		
			 from the <span class="dept-text">old-OS</span> dept.
		
		</span>
	</div>
</header>

<div class="body" id="fhbody-174548922">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-174548922" class="p">
			
		 	
				Slashdot reader <a href="https://www.slashdot.org/~Thelasko">Thelasko</a> shared <a href="https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/southwest-cloudstrike-windows-3-1/">Friday's article from <em>Digital Trends</em></a>:

<i>Nearly every flight in the U.S. is grounded right now following a CrowdStrike <a href="https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/fix-deployed-says-firm-at-center-of-global-it-outage/">system update error</a> that's affecting everything from travel to mobile ordering at Starbucks &mdash; but not Southwest Airlines flights. Southwest is still flying high, unaffected by the outage that's plaguing the world today, and that's apparently because it's using Windows 3.1.<br> <br>


Yes, Windows 3.1 &mdash; an operating system that is 32 years old. Southwest, along with UPS and FedEx, haven't had any issues with the CrowdStrike outage. In <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2024/07/19/business/delta-american-airlines-flights-outage-intl-hnk/index.html">responses to CNN</a>, Delta, American, Spirit, Frontier, United, and Allegiant all said they were having issues, but Southwest told the outlet that its operations are going off without a hitch. <a href="https://x.com/dalmaer/status/1814331722072256590">Some are attributing</a> that to Windows 3.1. Major portions of Southwest's systems <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/hershshefrin/2022/12/31/can-southwest-airlines-fix-its-systemic-weaknesses-in-the-new-year/">are reportedly built</a> on Windows 95 and Windows 3.1...</i> <br>

<strong>UPDATE: </strong> Reached for comment, Southwest "would not confirm" that's it's using Windows 3.1, <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/travel/article/southwest-escapes-problems-worldwide-outage-19584828.php">reports SFGate</a>. But they did get this quote from an airline analyst:<br> <br>

&#226;oeWe believe that Southwest&#226;(TM)s older technology kept it somewhat immune from the issues affecting other airlines today."<br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
	</div>
	<aside class="grid_24 view_mode">
		
